<!DOCTYPE html>

<title>Google+ User Feed</title>

<%- partial('head-partial') %>

<script src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.7.0/jquery.min.js"></script>
<script>
    $(function() {
        $('form').submit(function() {
            var userId = $('form input[name=user]').val()
            if (/^[0-9]+$/.test(userId)) {
                open(userId)
            } else {
                alert("'" + userId + "' is not valid user id")
            }
            return false
        })
    })
</script>

<div class="container">

    <h1>Google+ User Feed</h1>

    <div class="alert-message block-message info">
        <p><strong>Export <a href="https://plus.google.com/">Google+</a> user activity to other 
            services</strong> like Twitter, Facebook or Google Reader.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Google+ doesn't provide any means to export user posts apart from using its API. This is a 
        convenience tool that creates an RSS feed so it can be easily integrated with other services. 
        An <a href="107383157816966336384" target="_blank">example</a> of what you get.</p>

    <div class="compact-box">
        <form id="feed-form" class="well">
            User id 
            <span class="label help" title="It is the big number in the user profile URL">?</span>
            <input name="user" placeholder="Eg, 123456789012345678901" />
            <input type="submit" class="btn primary" value="Get the feed" />
        </form>
    </div>

    <h2>Common uses</h2>

    <ul>
        <li>
            <h3>Publish your Google+ activity on other social networks</h3>
            <p>There are many services that allow you to publish on Twitter, Facebook or Linkedin 
                from an RSS feed. Popular ones are <a href="http://ifttt.com/">ifttt</a> 
                (<a href="http://ifttt.com/recipes/1362">recipe for Twitter</a>), 
                <a href="http://dlvr.it/">dlvr.it</a> and 
                <a href="http://twitterfeed.com/">TwitterFeed</a>.</p>
            <p><span class="label">Hint</span> 
                <a href="https://plus.google.com/me" target="_blank">This is your profile URL</a></p>
            <p><span class="label">Pro tip</span> These services check feeds regularly but if you 
                don't want to wait many of them also allow you to check them manually.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <h3><strong>Follow Google+ users from your preferred feed reader</strong></h3>
            <p>This is a good option if you are already using a feed reader (like Google Reader), 
                follow few users and don't want to open Google+ site to see what's new.</p>
            <p>Unfortunately this tool exports a title for every post but not a body, so you 
                probably want to use other similar services which do include it like 
                <a href="http://rss2lj.net/g+">Google+ to RSS</a> or 
                <a href="http://plusfeed2.appspot.com/">PlusFeed</a>.</p>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Source code and feedback</h2>

    <p>Please visit the <a href="https://github.com/frosas/google-plus-user-feed">GitHub project page</a>.</p>
</div>

<%- partial('body-end-partial') %>
